accessibility.text: Presenter notes 	The other measurement is how the sensitivity to first-order motion changes. One way we can measure sensitivity to first-order motion is to take the same data — a psychometric function of the position displacement — and collect it at different values of first-order motion, and see what the differences are. 	Here the red lines indicate where the motion was weak, 0.1, and the blue lines indicate where it was stronger, 0.2. Now when you make this change the sensitivity to spacing doesn’t change — the red and blue plots are parallel. But when you add a bit of first-order motion, you get a shift — you bias the appearance of the motion one way or the other. The degree of this shift is indicated by these black arrows.

What you can see here is that when spacing is narrow, in the left column, increasing the energy of the first order motion makes a big difference, but when spacing is wider it makes hardly any difference — actually the difference is a bit negative if you follow those arrows.
